kathryne young the clayman institute for gender research skip to main content standford university the clayman institute for gender research the clayman institute for gender research home programs news strategic focus events about research fellowships library media center gender news no news found events no events found you are here home people kathryne young kathryne young ph d candidate department of sociology kathryne m young is a sixth year phd candidate in the sociology department at stanford university and recently received her jd from stanford law school her research interests include sociology of law legal consciousness criminal procedure social psychology qualitative research methods and sociology of gender her dissertation draws a six week participant observation study of hawaiian cockfights and uses the fights as a lens through which to discuss masculinity legal consciousness and localism young's other projects include a study of rights consciousness in the criminal context and a doctrinal and sociological analysis of gays and lesbians on criminal juries young has taught a variety of undergraduate classes including qualitative research methods the sociology of criminal procedure and several writing courses you can learn more about young and her work at www kathrynemyoung com donate make a donation social links facebook twitter youtube scribd contact serra house 589 capistrano way stanford ca 94305 8640 map 650 723 1994 gender email stanford edu
